					<dt class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-28974">
<span class="avatar"><a href="http://www.blogger.com/profile/01728934892670570446" rel="nofollow"><img alt='' src='http://www.melskitchencafe.com/wp-includes/images/blank.gif' class='avatar avatar-40 photo avatar-default' height='40' width='40' /></a></span>
<span class="comment_num"><a href="#comment-28974" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="nofollow">87</a></span>
<span class="comment_author"><a href='http://www.blogger.com/profile/01728934892670570446' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Melanie</a></span>
<span class="comment_time">March 5, 2010 at 2:40 am</span>

					</dt>
					<dd class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
<div class="format_text" id="comment-body-28974">
<p>Anonymous &#8211; because this soup recipe doesn&#39;t have processed cheese in it, it has a different texture than a broccoli cheese soup made with, say, Velveeta cheese. It should still be thick and creamy and smooth, but you may get a little texture difference because of the flour. Although, it shouldn&#39;t be super gritty. Sometimes if the flour and butter isn&#39;t cooked for a few minutes before adding the milk, you can get a strong flour taste. Hope that helps!</p>
</div>
					</dd>
